<Base
  title="AXS components, Jeff Mills"
  description="Component browser and code samples from the AXS design system. Vue 3 SFCs and the composables they're built on."
>
  <p class="project-back"><a href="/projects/axs">&laquo; back to axs</a></p>
  <h1 class="page-title">axs · components</h1>
  <p class="project-meta">
    <span class="project-year">2020-2025</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span class="project-status">proprietary</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span>{axsVue.length} vue + {axsWc.length} custom elements</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span>vue 3 + composition api</span>
  </p>

  <p class="page-lede">
    Two parallel listings: the Vue 3 single-file components in
    <code>axs-vue</code> (the canonical source) and the custom elements
    in <code>axs-web-components</code> (the compiled output, registered
    via <code>defineCustomElement</code>). Plus the composables layer
    underneath. Featured component samples below.
  </p>

  <aside class="callout">
    <span class="callout-label">Proprietary, code samples only</span>
    <p>
      Component directory names are listed in full so the breadth of the
      system is legible; the source of all but the highlighted samples
      stays in the private repo.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">axs-vue · {axsVue.length} components</h2>
  <p class="section-lede">
    The canonical Vue 3 source. Featured samples marked
    <span class="featured-marker">[&dagger;]</span>.
  </p>

  <pre class="component-tree" set:html={axsVueTreeHtml}></pre>

  <h2 class="section-title">axs-web-components · {axsWc.length} elements</h2>
  <p class="section-lede">
    The compiled custom elements registered via <code>defineCustomElement</code>.
  </p>

  <pre class="component-tree" set:html={axsWcTreeHtml}></pre>

  <h2 class="section-title">composables · {composables.length}</h2>
  <p class="section-lede">
    The reactive primitives the components are built on. Featured sample
    below.
  </p>

  <pre class="component-tree single-col" set:html={composablesTreeHtml}></pre>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">sample · AxsButton</h2>
  <p>
    A direct upgrade of the FASET button to Vue 3 + TypeScript +
    <code>defineCustomElement</code>. The <code>Props</code>
    interface is parsed by <code>vue-docgen-api</code> and emitted as
    web-types JSON for IDE autocomplete and the MCP server. Same
    component used by Vue consumers directly and by Angular / AEM /
    raw HTML through the registered custom element.
  </p>

  <Code code={axsButtonSample} lang="vue" theme={theme} />

  <p class="caption">
    <code>libs/axs-vue/src/components/AxsButton/AxsButton.vue</code>
  </p>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">sample · AxsAccordionController</h2>
  <p>
    A tiny component that shows the composables layer in action.
    <code>useHostElement</code> binds reactively to the wrapping custom
    element. <code>useDeeplySlottedElement</code> finds slotted
    descendants by tag name across the shadow DOM boundary.
    <code>useDOMElement</code> exposes a reactive handle to an external
    element by id. Each composable encapsulates a normally-awkward shadow
    DOM access pattern as a typed reactive API.
  </p>

  <Code code={axsAccordionSample} lang="vue" theme={theme} />

  <p class="caption">
    <code>libs/axs-vue/src/components/AxsAccordion/AxsAccordionController.vue</code>
  </p>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">sample · useViewport composable</h2>
  <p>
    The Vue 3 replacement for FASET&rsquo;s <code>v-show-at</code> /
    <code>v-hide-at</code> directives. Same shape as
    <a href="https://vueuse.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">VueUse</a>
    but pre-dates it as a custom in-house primitive; matchMedia listeners
    drive a single reactive viewport object that any component can
    <code>computed()</code> off.
  </p>

  <Code code={useViewportSample} lang="typescript" theme={theme} />

  <p class="caption">
    <code>libs/axs-vue/src/composables/viewport/index.ts</code>
  </p>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">patterns you'll see across the library</h2>
  <ul class="proof-list">
    <li>
      <strong>TypeScript <code>Props</code> interfaces with TSDoc.</strong>
      Drives both the component API and the
      <code>axs-automation:jweb-types</code> build-time IDE metadata
      generator. One source of truth for prop types, descriptions, and
      defaults.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Composables, not mixins.</strong> Vue 3 Composition API
      throughout. The <code>composables/</code> directory holds the
      reactive primitives (host, slot, viewport, resize, click-outside,
      DOM-by-id) the components compose with.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Shadow DOM-safe by default.</strong> Components ship with
      shadow DOM enabled; tokens propagate via CSS custom properties so
      theming pierces the boundary without the component needing to know.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Cross-element reactive wiring.</strong> Components like
      <code>AxsAccordion</code> split responsibilities across multiple
      tags (panel, trigger, controller, indicator) with reactive
      attribute binding between them through the composables.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Custom-element-aware directives.</strong>
      <code>v-click-outside</code> handles both regular DOM and shadow
      DOM. <code>v-intersect</code> uses a single shared
      <code>IntersectionObserver</code> and a WeakMap of callbacks.
      Same pattern as FASET; refined for Vue 3.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <p class="project-foot">
    Back to <a href="/projects/axs">AXS overview</a>
    &middot; Compare to <a href="/projects/faset/components">FASET components</a>
  </p>
</Base>

